"1350":"1350","Mouswald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Mouswald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carruthers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a place near Ecclefechan in Dumfries, locally pronounced ‘kridders’. The name is early recorded as <i>Carrothres</i> or <i>Caer Ruther</i>, and derives from British <i>caer</i> ‘fort’ + a personal name."],"variants":[{"name":"Crothers","meanings":["Irish (northern, especially Down): variant of Scottish   Carruthers  ."]},{"name":"Carrothers","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Carruthers  ."]},{"name":"Cruthers","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   Carruthers  ."]},{"name":"Carrithers","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Carruthers  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain; it was once common in Yorkshire."]},{"name":"Caruth","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Carruthers  ."]},{"name":"Cruthis","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish and northern Irish   Carruthers  . This surname is found mainly in IL and NC."]},{"name":"Cruthirds","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish and northern Irish   Carruthers  . This surname is found mainly in MS."]},{"name":"Carothers","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Carruthers  ."]},{"name":"Caruthers","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Carruthers  ."]},{"name":"Carithers","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Carruthers  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Third Laird Robert Carruthers of Mouswald was born about 1335, in Mouswald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Second Laird William Carruthers of Mouswald. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1335–":"umbes 1335–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1345–Male":"1345–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1300–1361":"1300–1361","before 1411":"enne 1411","1335":"1335","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1330":"1330","about 1335":"umbes 1335","1361":"1361","1350":"1350","Mouswald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Mouswald, Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1335–":"noin 1335–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","1345–Male":"1345–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1300–1361":"1300–1361","before 1411":"ennen vuotta 1411","1335":"1335","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1330":"1330","about 1335":"noin 1335","1361":"1361","1350":"1350","Mouswald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Mouswald, Dumfriesshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1335–":"environ 1335–Décédé","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1335–Male":"1335–Décédé","1345–Male":"1345–Décédé